Neither Spouse Nor Kin: The Denver Residents Classified as 'Partners' in the 1900 Federal Census¶

Teddy Scott¶

Final Project for Data: A User Manual (CU Denver, Fall 2021)¶

Introduction¶

For over a year now, I have been working on a project to locate the earliest traceable evidence of queer individuals and communities in post-colonial Denver. Using Denver City Directories from 1870-1914 and Sanborn Fire Insurance Maps, I mapped potentially-queer events or individuals that gained visibility through newspaper articles and police reports. The results revealed a tight cluster (with a one and a half block radius) of six out seven of the locatable instances of non-vaudevillian female impersonation between 1877 and 1901. Locations of potential sodomy occurrencesthe other archetypal instance of cis-male queer behavior or individualshowever, seemed to loosely follow streetcar routes more widely within the working-class neighborhoods of the city. Historians who have studied queer neighborhoods in other cities during the pre-World War I era through the 1920s have consistently pointed to the existence of a small community of female impersonators in each city. They were often described as male prostitutes who adopted effeminate names, garments, and mannerisms to visibly indicate their sexual availability to men from outside of their community. This pattern supported the likelihood that I was looking at such a community in Denver, however, my timeline (1877-1901) was earlier than any of the examples from New York City, Portland, San Francisco, or Chicago. (Chauncey,47-62; Jim Elledge, 14-27; Boag, loc. 1213-1244)



Flash forward to this past October, I read Dan Bouks blog entry about his small exploration into the Partners of Greenwich Village. Prompted by the research of Ansley Erickson, Bouk sought to find out if those labeled as a Partner to the Head of a household in the 1940 Federal Census could ever indicate the presence of queer individuals or communities. Bouk calculated the likelihoodfrom the total entries of partners in the censusthat a given enumerator would record a partner in their assigned district. He calculated that an average of less than three (2.96) partners were recorded by each enumerator, however the enumerator who recorded the data from Greenwich Village in NYCa widely known gay neighborhood during this era according to George Chaunceyrecorded twelve partners within her district alone. At first glance this would strongly support the existence of a queer neighborhood, so I decided to apply the same method to my own research about Denver. As I studied and mapped the nearly 160 census recordings of Partners in Denver in 1900--the earliest year to use the label, at least in Denver--I asked myself two overarching questions: are there queer individuals represented within this data? And, can these individuals indicate or confirm the existance of larger queer communities?

Methodology¶

Thanks to the accessible and searchable databases of ancestry.com, I was able to filter through the 1900 Federal Census to list all those who were labeled as a Partner in Denver. As I mentioned above, the search returned nearly 160 census entries, from which I transcribed twenty-two values of data for each individual onto a spreadsheet, ranging from "Marital Status" to the "Occupation of [the] Head [of the household]." This proved to be a challenge, especially when I encountered messy penmanship or data that had been obscured during the digitization process. In these cases I wrote "illegible" for the value of the given row. I exported the spreadsheet as a csv (coma separated value) file named "1900-Denver-Partners-Census.csv," and saved it to my Project folder for easy accessibility. I was then able to open and read the csv file with the Python command pd.read_cvs() by inserting the filepath "1900-Denver-Partners-Census.csv" within the parentheses, which produced a table of the data contained in the csv file.

Once my data set was assigned to a workable dataframe, my next task was to cross-analyse the data through various filters, and eventually to map them. To do this, I had to define a function that applied one or more conditions to the denver_df dataframe. These took the form of simple equations that selected a column within the dataframe and stated a condition to be applied to the value, such as "Birthplace" == "USA," which searches through the dataframe and only selects individuals who were born in the United States. If I wanted to further specify that this filter should also display households with only two people ("Size of Household" == 2), I simply connected the statements with an "&" symbol, allowing me to add as many conditions and I desired to a given filter. Therefore, if I wanted to create a filter that--when applied to the denver_df dataframe--only showed me individuals who were both American-born and lived in a household of only two people, I would run the following code:

In [5]:
american_pairs_filter = (denver_df['Birthplace']=='USA') & (denver_df['Size of Household'] == 2)

I then had to turn the filter into its own dataframe that could be passed through various functions, from data summaries to geolocated maps. Like many of the processes up this point, this only required a simple defining statement that assigned the filtered results from denver_df to a new dataframe called american_pairs_df.

In [6]:
american_pairs_df = denver_df[american_pairs_filter]

This new dataframe will only display individuals within the dataset who meet both the conditions of American-born and living in a household size of 2.

This filter can only tell us a small fragment of the story of this dataset, so naturally I created and graphed many filters of varying complexities to incorporate within my analysis. The final step, however, was to map these filters so that I could identify potential patterns of settlement among the different demographics represented in the data set.

In order to begin mapping these filters, I needed to install a Python package named GeoPy to give me access to a range of geocoding API services. I was able to do this with the !pip command, which installs Python packages (!pip install geopy). Because it does not require an API key, I chose the program Nominatum among GeoPy's API services to read the addresses contained within the dataframe and produce geographic coordinates. I was able to import the program from the newly installed GeoPy with the following command:

In [9]:
from geopy.geocoders import Nominatim

I now needed a variable through which to run Nominatum, much like how I assigned the command to read my csv file to the dataframe denver_df. I assigned the variable "geolocator" to the program, naming the process "Teddy's mapping app" for clarity. Now, in order to use Nominatum's API services, I could plug in the more-compatible command of "geolocator."

In [10]:
geolocator = Nominatim(user_agent="Teddy's mapping app", timeout=2)

To obtain the actual longitudes and latitudes of each listed address, I first had to define a function that applied the "geolocator" command to the "Location" column in my csv file. Therefore in the following code, I assigned "place" to the "Location" column, and then assigned the geocode command to "location," specifying "place" in the parentheses in order to apply geocoding to the "Location". Finally, I specified for the code to "return" the geolocated "address" , "latitude," "longitude," and "importance." If a "Location" was left blank in a given row, I specified for the function to return the phrase "Not Found."

In [11]:
def find_location(row):
    
    place = row['Location']
    
    location = geolocator.geocode(place)
    
    if location != None:
        return location.address, location.latitude, location.longitude, location.raw['importance']
    else:
        return "Not Found", "Not Found", "Not Found", "Not Found"

With the "find_location" command defined, I applied it to the dataframe denver_df with the df.apply() function, filling the parentheses with the new command. I also included specifications that the command was supposed to be applied to the "columns" axis (x-axis) and that this function should "expand" the resulting table.

In [12]:
#denver_df[['address', 'lat', 'lon', 'importance']] = denver_df.apply(find_location, axis="columns", result_type="expand")

However, in order to digitally map all of the legible addresses in my dataset, I needed to import a Python library called "Folium," which contained an open-source repository of interactive digital maps. I also had to define a function that would load the map to a default set of geographic coordinates and a default zoom level. Keeping it simple, I named this function denver_map.

In [16]:
import folium
In [17]:
denver_map = folium.Map(location=[39.75, -105.005], zoom_start=15)

If you were to run this fuction on its own, it would generate a blank OpenStreetMap-generated map of the city of Denver. However, my goal was to create a map with individual pins marking each address recorded in my data set. Therefore I established the command create_map_markers to create pins using folium and the values listed in the "lat" and "lon" columns. I completed this code with the add_to() command, filling the parentheses with "denver_map" and therefore specifying which map these pins were supposed to be added to. Once create_map_markers was fully defined, I used the df.apply() command to apply this new function to the locate_partners_df, which took the coordinates listed in the dataframe and marked each one on the denver_map.

In [18]:
def create_map_markers(row, map_name):
    folium.Marker(location=[row['lat'], row['lon']], popup=row['Name'],icon=folium.Icon(color="gray",icon="user", prefix='fa')).add_to(denver_map)
    
denver_map = folium.Map(location=[39.75, -105.005], zoom_start=15)
locate_partners_df.apply(create_map_markers, map_name=denver_map, axis='columns')
denver_map

Main Analysis¶

When I cross-analyzed the various filtered dataframes, several smaller demographical stories began to take form, as well as a larger picture of a predominantly working-class population living in varying degrees of financial and racial vulnerability. One particularly defining aspect of the households that contained people labled as "partner[s]" was that multiple incomes were needed to support the inhabitants. While some households evidently only required two incomes, a little more than half of all the "partner[s]" in Denver came from households of three or more working individuals. Given the working-class nature of nearly all of the occupations listed, it seems reasonable to suppose that those who lived in larger households did so to live under less financial strain, and that living in smaller (unrelated) groups was a luxury not everyone could afford. Therefore, the lable of "partner" in Denver's 1900 Census was primarily used to reflect a financial arrangement that, by nature, classified the household inhabitants as well outside of the relative financial stability of the middle class.

But aside from a shared restriction of household income, the individuals contained within this data set largely reflect the ways in which different racial, ethnic, and occupational groups banded together and consequently shaped the neighborhoods around them. In fact, nearly half of all of those labled as partners were immigrants (63 immigrants vs. 73 American-born individuals), with over half of those having immigrated from China (39 Chinese vs. 34 non-Chinese). Of the 34 immigrants who did not originate from China, the majority came from Western Europe and Canada. The following chart breaks down the country of origin of all of the immigrant partners in Denver in 1900:

Occupation by Naturalization¶

Of all 73 immigrant partners, only 13 women were recorded, none of whom immigrated from China. Conversely, of the 83 American-born subjects in the data set, 31 were labeled as women. Nearly all of the subjects (from all demographics) worked in working-class occupations, but as you can see from the following pie charts, the occupations available to certain populations were restricted to those that were believed to be socially "acceptable" for certain demographics.

Occupation by Race¶

According to these charts, race drastically affected the occupations that were available to a person more than a person's immigrant status. The only three races listed in the data set were "white" (108 subjects), "chinese" (41 subjects), and "black" (7 subjects). If we were to shift gears toward race rather than naturalization, the true differences in the occupations that were available to the white vs. non-white population becomes glaringly apparent, even with the large discrepancies in population size.

There's nothing ambiguous about the occupational niches that Chinese and Black residents were restricted to. While white working-class residents of 1900 Denver worked an array of manual labor, skilled labor, and service jobs, the overwhelming majority of Chinese residents were restricted to "laundry" work, while Black residents were mainly servants or manual laborers.

Size of Household by Race¶

With such an obviously restricted job market for residents of color, it seems plausible that these households found themselves under greater financial strain than their white counterparts, and were therefore more likely to live in groups of three or more housemates to save on the cost of urban living. While significantly more white individuals lived in group-living situations (three or more housemates) than either the Chinese or Black populations, this seems to be due only to their status as the overwhelming racial majority. In fact, those who lived in pairs (only two housemates) still constituted the narrow majority of white households. This lends me to believe that my earlier hypothesis, that larger households reflected greater financial vulnerability, is at least partially true. Therefore, it begs the questions: why did pairs of individuals (who were not spouses or blood-relations) choose to live together? Was it out of financial necessity? Or was there another reason?

A personal bias that I believe is necessary to point out is that I primarily processed and analyzed this dataset through a queer lens, searching particularly for indications of same-sex couples and possibly larger queer communities. This certainly affected my research process throughout as limited time frames often require one to bookend their focus in order to be productive. Though my analysis takes most demographics into account, from this point onward I will focus on those who lived in pairs and the various factors that potentially enabled or restricted the formation of such unconventional (for the period) household units.

Mapping Denver's Pairs¶

In order to gain a clearer picture of the factors that potentially facilitated the settlement of pairs, I needed to see the spatial relationship (or lack thereof) between the different demographic groups contained within the data set. Therefore, I applied dozens of different filters to the dataframe locate_partners_df (the one that contained the longitude and latitude measurements of each address) to see if I could notice any patterns. Indeed, there were three primary details that caught my eye.

The first was the settlement pattern of the different immigrant groups. While non-Chinese immigrants often housed together with fellow countrymen/women, they seemed to settle near their places of employement rather than within larger ethnic communities. Chinese immigrants, on the other hand, settled in three distinct clusters and were rarely found outside of these apparent enclaves. While mapping the addresses of Denver's white immigrant groups displayed little spatial connection to other ethnically-related households, the following map shows the clear clustering of Chinese individuals within their own communities:

Map 3 - All Chinese Partners

The top cluster of map pins--encompassing the area between 19th and 23rd Streets, and Blake and Curtis Streets--generally surrounded the city's Red-Light District and was historically known as Denvers China Town. Another (possibly smaller) community sat four blocks away, just southeast of Union Station, and the largest and most densely populated enclave filled the triangle formed by Broadway, Stout, and 15th Streets. Contrarily, while half of the pins marking Black households fell within the historically Black neighborhood of Five Points--above Park Avenue--they were too few and too spread apart to reflect any apparent spatial connection to one another. However, when I mapped all of the addresses of the "partners" who were living in pairs, a very different landscape took form:

Map 4 - All Paired Partners

The second detail that I noticed was the general clustering of pins along Champa Street (between 15th and 20th Streets) and along 15th and 16th Streets (between Champa and Tremont Streets), creating somewhat of an L-shape. This cluster appears fairly unremarkable as it currently stands, however, it was enough to draw my attention as I moved forward. I wondered if this cluster was near an important transportation route, but streetcar lines literally ran along the streets on either side of Champa, but not along Champa itself. This part of the city had the densest network of streetcars, so its difficult to identify any feature that would have made this particular corridor desirable (or at least accessible) to paired "partner[s]." This made me wonder if there could be a queer context to this pattern of settlement. So, I asked myself, which combination of demographic factors generate the most likely situation for a queer relationship? And which factors generate the least likely situation?

While same-sex group living arrangements could certainly lend to homosexual behavior due to the homosocial environment, such relationships are nearly impossible to bring to light without access to personal correspondences or records of arrest [on charges of sodomy]. It also seems that those who partnered into households with others within their marginalized immigrant or racial communities, therefore partnering among the similarly marginalized for survival rather than romantic partnership, are less likely to reflect a queer context within their living situations. Unsurprisingly, those labeled as married, even without their spouse present, would be less likely to form a household from a homosexual relationship and then report both their married status and their unusual same-sex coupling to an enumerator. Therefore, I created a map that would show me all unmarried pairs of the same gender and set the map markers to display the individual's recorded "Race."

Map 5 - Unmarried, Same-Gendered Pairs

Not very much actually changed between this and the last map except that some of the outlying markers disppeared, further highlighting the Champa/16th Street "L." This apparent stasis also shows how paired "partner[s]" in general were overwhelmingly unmarried, and living with someone of the same (listed) gender. While those who lived along the 16th/Champa Street corridors are a surprising mixture of American-born and non-Chinese immigrant individuals, if you click on the map markers you might notice that all but one of the seventeen pins within the L-shape mark "white" households. However, since the vast majority of the pins on this map represent white households, this tells us little about this pattern of settlement. What geographic or demographic details motivated so many unmarried, same-gendered pairs to settle so densely in this area? The one non-white household--labeled as "chinese--could hint at an answer.

If you scroll back up to "Map 3 - All Chinese Partners," it may become apparent that the L-shape in question in fact borders and even shares space with the largest and densest Chinese enclave. This wouldn't be particularly unusual among working-class households,--which the vast majority were--however, there seems to be a growing list of geographic and demographic qualities applicable to the "L" corridor:

  • Same-gendered individuals living in pairs.

  • Both are unmarried.

  • Nearly all have working-class jobs.

  • Nearly all are labeled as white.

  • The population tightly borders and even cuts into a Chinese racial community.

Like I mentioned before, I couldn't help but view this data through a queer lens, and so far these results suggest a promising possibility that this population cluster could include a certain density of queer individuals, and therefore potentially a queer community. Evidently, unmarried same-sex pairs gravitated toward the liminal space between (and within) the marginalized Chinese community and the rest of the larger working-class neighborhood. This nearness to other marginalized communities was mirrored in examples of queer neighborhoods from other cities, as well as within my own research regarding the community of female impersonators near the Red-Light District. In fact, my community of female impersonators also bordered a prominent Chinese enclave, however in a much seedier part of town (where even working-class homosexual couples would presumably not want to associate with). Paired with the fact that several of the outlying unmarried same-sex pairs (not within the L-shaped corridor) represent households geographically beholden to ethnic communities or shared occupationslike servants working and living in a Capitol Hill mansionthis cluster of unmarried same-sex pairs appears more and more eccentric.

A queer context cannot be conclusively applied to these results without further research into the area's built environment in 1900, as well as into the individuals in question. However, there was one final map filter that I wanted to explore in case it could add any more certainty (or doubt) to the potential of a queer working-class neighborhood: unmarried, same-gendered pairs who did not work in the same occupation. Now, while shared occupations among paired housemates could certainly suggest another element of convenience or even survival, it doesnt seem to necessarily prove nor disprove a queer relationship. However, two people of the same gender living together with different occupations adds another level of likelihood that a given household might reflect a possible queer dynamic because another element of convenience has been removed. Unsurprisingly, the map of this filter generated less-than conclusive results, but compelling nonetheless:

Map 6 - Unmarried, Same-Gendered Pairs with Different Occupations

While the pins within the L-shape have thinned out considerably, so have all the rest. In fact, the "L" remains the most densely populated area by those included in this filter. A few other factors further complicate these results at their face value. Two of the outlying pins actually contain a NaN value for the occupation of one their inhabitants, meaning that the partners don't conclusively work in separate occupations. Furthermore, four additonal outlying pins technically label the occupants as having different occupations from one another, but further inspection shows that these occupations are tied to the same establishment, such as a laundry, church, or domestic workers in the same house. That's a total of seven outlying pins that should be disqualified from the intention of this filter, further highlighting the ever-illusive L-shaped corridor. If you run the following code below, then re-run Map 6 (in cell 83), perhaps you can spot these discrepancies yourself!

In [42]:
def create_map_markers(row, map_name):
    folium.Marker(location=[row['lat'], row['lon']], popup=row['Occupation of Head'],icon=folium.Icon(color="pink",icon="user", prefix='fa')).add_to(denver_map)

Conclusion¶

Apart from its intended value in aiding my quest to uncover Denver's earliest post-colonial queer communities, this data set could be useful for other researchers who are studying Denver's working-class, immigrant, or racial/ethnic populations. Though immigrant women were scarcely represented in the data (or not represented at all in the case of the Chinese), insights into the vulnerability of immigrant or working-class American-born women could be gathered from those who grouped together for survival, or other reasons. An inherent flaw with this data set is directly related to the inevitable element of human error involved with transcribing one's own data. I realized late in the project that I neglected to include the race of the Head of the Household in the original spreadsheet. Though I took note during the trancription process that I did not see any multiracial households, to not include that column in the data set was a deeply flawed oversight. Such information would certainly make this data set more useful for others, and I intend to eventually take the time to add it in.

While mapping this data through different filters did not conclusively illuminate any queer communities--at least not without further research--the settlement patterns along 16th and Champa Streets certainly grabbed my attention and beg further examination. In the very least, I have found an area of the city where racial and cultural boundaries (which were deeply ingrained in the aggressive white supremacist ideology of the period) were blurred and unconventional family units found homes among others like themselves, queer or not. If this data set can lead others to any interesting or useful conclusions about the "Partner[s]" of Denver in 1900, I will consider my time very well spent.
